{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.03,0.01,0.7,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2492"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65945"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man is admitted to a peripheral hospital with a widespread erythematous tender rash, fever and general malaise. One week prior he commenced allopurinol for gout. Within 12 hours, the rash had appeared and now has rapidly progressed to involve 50% body surface area with large fluid-filled bullae and epidermal detachment. There is oral mucosal involvement. The Nikolsky sign is positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medical team suspects a severe drug reaction and with the on-call dermatology registrar, arranges for skin biopsy and transfer to the nearest burns unit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following options is a main prognostic factor in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Time from onset to burns unit admission","Class of medication associated","Patient gender","Extent of skin detachment","History of severe drug reactions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN), which is a medical emergency. SCORTEN is a severity score that predicts mortality in TEN patients. One point is scored for each of the criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge \u0026gt;40 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPresence of a malignancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart rate \u0026gt;120\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial percentage of \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E \u0026gt;10%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum urea level \u0026gt;10 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum glucose level \u0026gt;14 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum bicarbonate level \u0026lt;20 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESCORTEN 0-1 = \u0026gt;3.2% predicted mortality\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESCORTEN 2 = \u0026gt;12.1% predicted mortality\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESCORTEN 3 = \u0026gt;35.3% predicted mortality\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESCORTEN 4 = \u0026gt;58.3% predicted mortality\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESCORTEN 5+ = \u0026gt;90% predicted mortality\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SCORTEN is a severity score that predicts mortality in toxic epidermal necrolysis.","Toxic epidermal necrolysis is a life-threatening condition often triggered by medications, requiring urgent medical attention.","The extent of skin detachment is a critical prognostic factor in toxic epidermal necrolysis."],"references":["Bastuji-Garin S, Fouchard N, Bertocchi M, Roujeau JC, Revuz J, Wolkenstein P. SCORTEN: a severity-of-illness score for toxic epidermal necrolysis. J Invest Dermatol. 2000 Aug;115(2):149-53. doi: 10.1046/j.1523-1747.2000.00061.x. PMID: 10951229. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10951229/","Labib A, Milroy C. Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574530/","Hoetzenecker W, Mehra T, Saulite I, Glatz M, Schmid-Grendelmeier P, Guenova E, Cozzio A, French LE. Toxic epidermal necrolysis. F1000Res. 2016 May 20;5:F1000 Faculty Rev-951. doi: 10.12688/f1000research.7574.1. PMID: 27239294; PMCID: PMC4879934. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4879934/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65945"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65945"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T06:50:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T06:51:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2492"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"create